# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
An equal pair is formed by two rows in the grid that have the same elements in corresponding positions.
We need to count the number of such equal pairs in the grid.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Create a map **gridRow** to store the **frequency** of each row in the grid.
The **key** of the map is a vector representing a row, and the value is the frequency of that row in the grid.
```
 map<vector<int>,int> gridRow;
```
- Iterate through each row in the grid and update the frequency in the gridRow map.
For each row row in the grid, increment gridRow[row] by 1.
```
for(auto x:grid){
            gridRow[x]++;
        }
```
- Create a temporary vector temp to store the elements of each column.
```
 vector<int>temp;
```
- Iterate through each column in the grid.

 For each column, iterate through the rows and store the   corresponding elements in the temp vector.
 This step effectively transposes the grid, allowing us to treat columns as rows
```
 for (int i = 0; i < grid.size(); i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < grid.size(); j++) {
                temp.push_back(grid[j][i]);  
            }
```
- Check if the temp vector exists as a key in the gridRow map.

If it does, increment ans by the frequency of the column stored in gridRow[temp].
Clear the temp vector to prepare it for the next column.
``` 
 if (gridRow.count(temp)) {
                ans += gridRow[temp]; 
            }
```
# Complexity
- Time complexity:**O(N^2)**
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:**O(N^2)**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code 1
