The first thing is to solve this question is to take a paper and pen and try to write the info and given and functions required. This helped me as earlier i used to just think in my head and directly go on coding just to find later that i missed a requirement and start over again.

Ok, firstly two functions requirement: 
changeRating(food,newRating) -> void
highestRated(cuisine) -> string food(in given cuisine)

Now for the first requirement: 
First thought might be simple unordered_map for fast updates of ratings
**unordered_map<string,int> foods_to_ratings**
Now the first requirement is easy and main bottleneck is second requirement. Also we need to keep in mind that we already choosen a **foods_to_ratings unordered_map** so we have to keep that updated too.

Second function takes a cuisine.

What if keep **unordered_map<string,vector<pair<int,string>> cuisine_to_ratings_food** where **string is cuisine given** and **vector stores the pair<ratings,food>** 
It's because i need to quickly decide which the highest rated food in **given cuisine** so i need **some food division based on cuisine**.
But now for highestRated food in that vector of cuisine_to_ratings_food[given_cuisine] i had to go over the take the entire vector to find highest rated food which will be not good as in worst case all given food can belong to same cuisine and so **it will take O(n) for each call of function** where  **n can be upto 2x10^4**
Also if any food ratings update by **changeRatings(food,newRatings)** then i need to 
(1) find cuisine of that food 
(2) remove the <Oldratings,food> pair from vector in cuisine_to_ratings_food[cusine]  
(3) add <needRatings,food> pair in that. ( Note [cuisine] in cuisinetoratingsfood used in operation (2) can be found by (1) operation and way to find (1) is given below) 
(4) Update the food_to_ratings unordered_map which too quick

### How to do (1) operation?
I need to find food's cuisine so either i can keep unordered_map<food,cuisine> or map for the same.

 ### How to the (2) operation?
 We can get the oldRatings of food by **food_to_Ratings unordered_map**

### What's the problem in this approach?
Obviously the O(n) for findHighestRated(cuisine) is there iterating the vector.
Also O(n) for deleting the pair<oldRatings,food> in changeRatings(food,newRatings) so that the findHighestRated() function works fine. 

### Where can we improve?
Ok so i need to cut down the effort for finding the highest rated cuisine and also deletion of pair<ratings,food>. 
Hmm the pair<ratings,food> is unique right? Since for every food only one rating is there at  a time so pair<ratings,food> is unique.
### What datastructure is good in maintaining unique set of values in some order and give fast retrieval and updation?
### That's set

**So instead of vector what if we store the pairs in set<ratings,food> with custom comparator which keeps the highest ratings food at first and if the ratings of more than one food items are same then keep the food in lexicographical order.**

**findHighestRated is O(1) since we just return the first pair of set in the cuisine division**.
After keeping set instead of vector let's see operation of changeRatings(food,newRatings):
(1) find cuisine of food by food_to_cuisine unordered map
(2) remove the <Oldratings,food> pair from vector in cuisine_to_ratings_food[cusine] 
in O(10.log(20000)) since for every comparison(in worst case) the strings time complexity for same ratings is O(10).
(3) add <needRatings,food> pair in that. ( same as removing a pair)
(4) Update the food_to_ratings unordered_map so that in operation (2) we can find OldRatings of food quickly.

