solutions.content:
Problem asks the number of pairs such that set bits(num1 and num2) + set bits(num1 or num2) must be >=k.

**Observations:**
One simple observation is that
**set_bits(num1 and num2) + set_bits(num1 or num2) is equal to set_bits(num1)+set_bits(num2) .**

We store each element's set bits count and element itself in a set so as to have unique pairs and also sorted pairs in order of their set bits count.

we copy the set to the vector so that we can perform two pointers method to count desired pairs.

**Working:**
Now answer of how two pointers method works 

ex. test case: nums = [1,2,3,1], k = 3
Pairs stored in vector: [{1,1},{1,2},{2,3}]
taking p=0 and q=vector_size -1

Now if(v[p].first+v[q].first>=k) 
taking q as a element of pair we can easily consider all indexes which are >=p to make pair with index q so ans=ans+2*(q-p).
Multiplied by 2  as for example (1,3) and (3,1) would count as 2 pairs.

Also one case  is that when q makes pair with itself so if v[q].first*2>=k then ans=ans+1.

**Complexity:**
Time complexity: O(nlogn)
space complexity: O(n)

**C++ Code:**
```
long long countExcellentPairs(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        long long ans=0;
        // initializing a set to only have unique pairs 
        // first element in a pair of set represent number of set bits 
        // second element in a pair of set represent number of number itself 
        set <pair<int,int>> s;

		//__builtin_popcount(int x) is a method used to count number of set bits in integer x
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            s.insert({__builtin_popcount(nums[i]),nums[i]});
        }

        // now coping the set to vector so that we can take 2 pointers 
        vector <pair<int,int>> v;
        for(auto it:s){
            v.push_back(it);
        }

        int p=0,q=v.size()-1;
        // ans stores the number of pairs
        while(p<=q){
            if(v[p].first+v[q].first>=k){
                if(2*v[q].first>=k){
                    ans++;
                }
                ans+=2*(q-p);
                q--;
            }
            else{
                p++;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

