**KEY IDEA :   n(A ∪ B) = n(A) + n(B) – n(A ∩ B)**
It is required in the problem that we have to find count of pairs where 
number of set bits of (A | B)  + number of set bits of (A & B) >= k
as  **union** in mathematics implies  **OR** in boolean algebra and **intersection** implies **AND** operation in boolean algebra.
therefore: 
n(A | B)= n(A) + n( B) - n( A & B)
**n(A) +n (B) = n(A| B) + n(A& B)**
 which imples 
 number of set bits of A + number of set bits of B = number of set bits (A) **OR** number of set bits of (B) + number of set bits( A) **AND** number of set bits(B) 
 Algorithm :
*  make a unique set of given integers and a initialize variable ans= 0.
*  Build a 32 size integer array to store the frequency of the numbers having same number of bits. ( An integer can hold up to 32 bits therefore 32 size array is used) .
*  Now we use two nested loops with iteration from 1 to 32 , to make pairs of A and B  and check if ( setbits(A ) + setBits (B) >=k) then ans = ans+ frequency[ bits(A) ]* freq[ bits(B)]
*  return the answer

