A very basic set theory principle states that for an overlapping set, the following holds true
			**n ( P ∪ Q ) = n(P) + n(Q) – n ( P ∩ Q)**
			where n() represent the size of set

now if we consider all the numbers as a set itself with each of its one bit as its element, 
then the question is basically asking ask to find the number of pairs of (P, Q) such that **n ( P ∪ Q )+n ( P ∩ Q) >= k**, 
which using set theory principle easily translates to finding pairs such that  **n(P)+n (Q) >= k**

In our case, n(P) is nothing but number of set bits in P. 

