# 1. Brute Force Code
### Approach
Checking all the possible pairs along with trivial function to finds the count of set bits in binary representation of a decimal number.

### Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n * n * number)

- Space complexity: O(n * 2)

```
class Solution {
    private static int countSetBits(int number){
        int count = 0;
        for(int bit=1;bit<=32;bit++){
            count += (number & 1);
            number >>= 1;
        }
        return count;
    }

    public long countExcellentPairs(int[] nums, int k) {
        Set<List<Integer>> set = new HashSet<>();
        for(int index1=0;index1<nums.length;index1++){
            for(int index2=0;index2<nums.length;index2++){
                int num1 = (nums[index1]|nums[index2]), num2 = (nums[index1]&nums[index2]);
                int setBitsInNum1 = countSetBits(num1), setBitsInNum2 = countSetBits(num2);
                if(setBitsInNum1 + setBitsInNum2 >= k){set.add(Arrays.asList(nums[index1],nums[index2]));}
            }
        }
        return (long)set.size();
    }
}

// Brute Force Approach - TLE
// Time Complexity : O(n*n*number)
// Space Complexity : O(n*2)
```


# 2. Brute Force Code With countBits Function Optimization 
### Approach
Checking all the possible pairs along with Brian Kernighan’s Algorithm to finds the count of set bits in binary representation of a decimal number instead of using trivial function.

### Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n * n * log(number))

- Space complexity: O(n * 2)
```
class Solution {

    // Brian Kernighan’s Algorithm
    private static int countSetBits(int number){
        int count = 0;
        while(number != 0){
            number = (number)&(number-1);
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }

    public long countExcellentPairs(int[] nums, int k) {
        Set<List<Integer>> set = new HashSet<>();
        for(int index1=0;index1<nums.length;index1++){
            for(int index2=0;index2<nums.length;index2++){
                int num1 = nums[index1], num2 = nums[index2];
                int setBitsInNum1 = countSetBits(num1), setBitsInNum2 = countSetBits(num2);
                if(setBitsInNum1 + setBitsInNum2 >= k){set.add(Arrays.asList(nums[index1],nums[index2]));}
            }
        }
        return (long)set.size();
    }
}

// Brute Force Approach - TLE
// Time Complexity : O(n*n*log(number))
// Space Complexity : O(n*2)

```

# 3. Code By Storing The setBits 
### Approach
Storing The setBits Of All The Numbers Of The Array And THen Applying The Two Sum Analogy.

### Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n * n * log(number))

- Space complexity: O(n *2)
```
class Solution {

    // Brian Kernighan’s Algorithm
    private static int countSetBits(int number){
        int count = 0;
        while(number != 0){
            number = (number)&(number-1);
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }

    private static int[] storeSetBits(int[] nums){
        int[] store = new int[nums.length];
        for(int index=0;index<nums.length;index++){store[index] = countSetBits(nums[index]);}
        return store;
    }

    private static long twoSumAnalogy(int[] nums, int[] store, int target){
        Set<List<Integer>> set = new HashSet<>();
        for(int index1=0,len=store.length;index1<len;index1++){
            for(int index2=0;index2<len;index2++){
                if(store[index1] + store[index2] >= target){
                    set.add(Arrays.asList(nums[index1],nums[index2]));
                }
            }
        }
        return (long)set.size();
    }

    public long countExcellentPairs(int[] nums, int k) {
        int[] store = new int[nums.length];
        store = storeSetBits(nums);
        return twoSumAnalogy(nums,store,k);
    }
}

// Brute Force Approach - TLE
// Time Complexity : O(n*n*log(number))
// Space Complexity : O(n*2)

```

# 4. Optimized Code Using The Counting Sort 
### Approach
- The Inclusion-Exclusion Principle
```
bits(num1 OR num2) + bits(num1 AND num2) = bits(num1) + bits(num2)
```
- Working 

    For all different ```a``` in ```nums```, counts its number of bits.

    Enumearte the number of bits ```k1``` and ```k2```,
    if ```k1 + k2 >= k```, we accumulate ``` count[k1] * count[k2] ```.
- Why we made countArray of size 30?
    Because it is given that ```max(nums[i]) = 1e9```, and we knwo that to represent any number in binary we needs a maximum of ```[log2(number)] + 1``` bits. Hence ```log2(10^9) ~ 9*log2(10) ~ 9*3.322 ~ 29.8 => [29.8] + 1 = 30```.

### Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n * log(number))

- Space complexity: O(n)
```
class Solution {
    public long countExcellentPairs(int[] nums, int k) {
        long countArray[] = new long[30], count = 0;
        Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>(); 
        for(int num : nums) set.add(num);                                    // O(n)    
        for(int num : set) countArray[Integer.bitCount(num)]++;              // O(nlog(number))
        for(int bit=1;bit<30;bit++){
            for(int bit_=1;bit_<30;bit_++){
                if(bit+bit_>=k) count += countArray[bit]*countArray[bit_];
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}

// Counting Sort Optimized Code 
// Time Complexity : O(n + nlog(number))
// Space Complexity : O(n) 

```

