* Let `bits(num1) = a, bit(num2) = b`.  be the bits set in `nums1` and `nums2`
* Let `bits(num1&num2) = c`, the number of set bits in both numbers.
* We want to compute `bits(num1&num2) + bits(num1|num2) `
* Let us partition each of the 32 bit positions into one of four cases and consider their contributions to the expression `bits(num1&num2) + bits(num1|num2)`:
* 
    |bit set in? |times counted in expression?| weight | total |
    |---|---|---|----|
    | `num1` only | counted in `num1|num2`| 1 | `a-c`
	| `num2` only | counted in `num1|num2`| 1 | `b-c`
	| `num1` & `num2` | counted in `num1&num2` and `num1|num2`| 2| `2c` 
	| neither num1 nor num2 | 0| 0| 0
Therefore 
* `bits(num1&num2) + bits(num1|num2) = `
* `(a-c) + (b-c) + 2c = `
*  `a + b`.

So given `nums1` with `bits(nums1) = a`, we need to find how many unique `nums2` exist such that `bits(nums) >= b`. 
We can use a set to dedupe the numbers, and a table `cnt` where `cnt[i] = b` counts how many numbers have exactly `b` bits.
Finally, we can use a prefix sum `prefix[i] = cnt[0] + cnt[1] ... cnt[i-1]` to find our answer quickly.
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long countExcellentPairs(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        vector<int> cnt(61);
        map<int,int> d; // deduplicate
        for(int n: nums){
            if(!d[n]++){
                ++cnt[bits(n)];
            }
        }
        vector<int> prefix(62);
        for(int i=1;i<62;++i){
            prefix[i] = cnt[i-1] + prefix[i-1];
        }
        long long sm = 0;
        int N = d.size();
        assert(prefix[0] == 0);
        assert(prefix.back() == N);
        for(auto [n, _]: d){
            int b = bits(n);
            int a = max(0, k-b);
            sm += N - prefix[a];
        }
        return sm;
    }
    int bits(int n){
        return __builtin_popcount(n);
    }
};
```

