solutions.content:
#### **Intuition:**
***We don't need to calculate each pair separately***
If we try to calculate, for each pair, `bits(a AND b) + bits(a OR b)`, it is going to take us O(n\xB2) to do it and we are going to run out of time. Fortunately, we don't need to do it: `bits(a OR b) = bits(a) + bits(b) - bits(a AND b)` (the bits of each number minus those we counted twice), and therefore, for each pair:

```bits(a AND b) + bits(a OR b) = bits(a AND b) + bits(a) + bits(b) - bits(a AND b) = bits(a) + bits(b)```
<br>
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7186dfc2-abcc-4e11-af7d-91b97d096bde_1661797225.3014474.gif)


***Nums contains duplicates***
We can maintain a Set of numbers already present and create a new array `arr` where we add every new number.

***Once we have converted the array to bit amounts, we can use a two-pointer strategy to move from O(n\xB2) towards O(n log n)***
If the set doesn't contain the number, we just add `bits(number)` to `arr`. All of this takes us [ O(n) ] time. Then we sort [ O(n log n) ] and use the two pointers strategy [ O(n) ].

***We don't care about the actual numbers, only the amount of "1's". We can exploit this to optimize the solution towards O(n) time***
Instead of adding `bits(number)` to the array as a new element, we can count how many distinct elements of `nums` have that many bits. `arr` will have, then, size 31, and for each unique element of nums, `arr[bits(number)]++`. Then the rest will be [ O(1) ] whatever the strategy we choose, and we can brute-force the solution (31x31 calculations => O(1)), or we can use two pointers, or we can use an inverse prefix-sum calculation since the problem asks for `bits(a) + bits(b) >= k` and not just ` == k`

With this strategy we avoid having to sort anything.

***This problem asks us for a long***
...but we mostly don't really care about that and can just add up the solution into a long at the end

***As a general rule we need to care for the corner cases AKA the case where a == b***
Here, fortunately, it sorts itself out with no additional code :)

#### **Solution**
**Java**
```
class Solution {
    public long countExcellentPairs(int[] nums, int k) {

        Set<Integer> uniques = new HashSet();
        int[] arr = new int[32]; // first element is unused, but it makes for code that is a bit cleaner

        for( int num : nums ) {
            if(!uniques.contains(num)) {
                uniques.add(num);
                arr[bits(num)]++;
            }
        }

        int acc = 0;
        int[] suffix = new int[32];
        for(int i = arr.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            acc += arr[i];
            suffix[i] = acc;
        }

        long ans = 0; // This is a long

        for(int i = 1; i < 32; i++) {

            if(k - i >= 32) {
                continue;
            }
            if(k - i < 1) {
                ans += arr[i] * suffix[1];
            } else {
                ans += arr[i] * suffix[k - i];
            }

        }

        return ans;
    }

    int bits(int num) {
        int ans = 0;
        while(num > 0) {
            if(num%2 != 0) {
                ans++;
            }
            num/=2;
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```
